  <para>
    <emphasis>Aliasing</emphasis> is what happens when you try to draw
    small objects on a computer screen where the size of the pixels is
    comparable to the size of the objects.  The &skel; edges shown in
    <xref linkend="Figure-aliasing"/> are one pixel wide, and the
    diagonals are not smoothly drawn.
    <emphasis>Antialiasing</emphasis> is a method for removing
    aliasing by making pixels bleed color into their neighbors, as
    shown in <xref linkend="Figure-antialiasing"/>.
  </para>
  <figure id="Figure-aliasing">
    <title>Aliasing</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/aliased.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/aliased.eps" format="eps"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	The effects of aliasing.  Observe the jagged portions of the
	diagonal skeleton edges.
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>
  <figure id="Figure-antialiasing">
    <title>Antialiasing</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/antialiased.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/antialiased.eps" format="eps"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	The same skeleton with antialiasing turned on.  The jagged
	lines are smooth, but everything is slightly blurry.
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>
  <para>
    Antialiasing can make line drawings look better, but it can cause
    problems when displaying filled polygons
    (<foreignphrase>e.g,</foreignphrase> <xref
    linkend="RegisteredClass-SkeletonMaterialDisplay"/> or <xref
    linkend="RegisteredClass-FilledContourDisplay"/>).  When the
    antialiasing algorithm attempts to smooth diagonal edges of
    adjacent polygons, it can leave some space in between, as shown in
    <xref linkend="Figure-antialiasing2"/>. For this reason, as well
    as because it can consume a fair amount of cpu time, antialiasing
    is <emphasis>off</emphasis> by default in &oof2;.
  </para>
  <figure id="Figure-antialiasing2">
    <title>Antialiasing Filled Polygons</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/antialiased2.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/antialiased2.eps" format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<simpara>
	  An antialiased display of filled polygons (<xref
	    linkend="RegisteredClass-SkeletonMaterialDisplay"/>).
	  Boundaries between the polygons are visible.
	</simpara>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/aliased2.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/aliased2.eps" format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<simpara>
	  A nonantialiased (<foreignphrase>i.e,</foreignphrase>
	  aliased) version of the same region.
	</simpara>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>

